pment of Latin American labour history across broad geographical, chronological and thematic perspectives, which seek to review and revisit key concepts at different levels. The contributions are closely linked to the most recent trends in Global Labour History and in turn, they enrich those trends. Here, authors from Argentina, Bolivia, Brazil, Mexico, Peru and Spain take a historical and sociological perspective and analyse a series of problems relating to labour relations. The chapters weave together different periods of Latin American colonial and republican history from the vice-royalties of New Spain (now Mexico) and Peru, the Royal Audiencia de Charcas (now Bolivia), Argentina and Uruguay (former vice-royalty of Río de La Plata) and Chile (former Capitanía General).  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 31. Jan 2022) 4aGeschichte der Arbeit. 4aKolonialismus. 4aLateinamerika. 4aModerne. 4aZwangsarbeit. 7aHISTORY / Social History.2bisacsh  aLatin America.  acolonialism.  alabour coercion.  alabour history.  amodernity.1 aBasualdo, Victoria, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCaruso, Laura, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCruz Terra, Paulo, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCruz Terra, Paulo, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aDe Vito, Christian G., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDe Vito, Christian G., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aFerreras, Norberto O., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGaleano, Diego, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aJulián-Vejar, Dasten, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aNúñez Espinel, Luz Ángela, 